AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;Scommessa vinta per i panettieri di Suresnes, comune dell'hinterland parigino, that managed to bake a baguette from 140 meters,> beating every world record. The Le Parisien newspaper reports it, which has documented the long work necessary to knead the typical French bread > and the over 11 hours of cooking to complete the rather complex enterprise. The highest recognition was not allowed to wait: the world's longest baguette title passed to France, formally assigned by Guinness World Records.> The previous record was reached by a team of Italian bakers on the shores of Lake Como>, who in 2019 had made a baguette from 132,62 meters, marking a very symbolic victory on the rival competitors of France, home of the iconic bread.
&nbsp;
"Suresnes is proud to have established the world's longest baguette record, which celebrates a national symbol of our gastronomy and artisans who perpetuate its know-how," said Mayor Guillaume Boudy, of the Horizons party.
&nbsp;
"I would like to congratulate Suresnes' bakers who participated in the preparation of baguette and who continue to maintain the traditions of sharing that are so essential for the conviviality of our city," added the first citizen of the municipality of the Hauts de Seine department. The six bakers of Suresnes -> who literally put their hands in dough with six of their counterparts of the 'Great Paris' bakers' union - kept us so much to bring back the record at home.&nbsp;>
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
At one point, they feared the worst, when "a piece of baguette touched the furnace ceiling. At that moment we were a little scared, because&nbsp; the last thing we wanted was that baguette broke," said one of the participants, Sylvain Lecarpentier. In order for the record to be approved by the authoritative Guinness World Records, the bread had to leave the oven perfectly intact.
&nbsp;
"We managed to recover the situation. Eventually the baguette did not break, the diameter was respected and we brought home the record. It is a great day and a great reason for pride," continued the owner of Fournil Henri IV, a bakery in the centre of Suresnes. A very long day for bakers, started in the middle of the night, starting from 3 am, to work the dough of almost 20 kneading machines of 5 kg each. "We finished around 16, which means 11 hours of cooking. That's exactly what we expected," they still reported to the media. Once it is clear, the huge baguette has been measured at a centimeter by inspectors:> a fundamental step to certify the record and ensure its entry into the list of Guinness World Records. At the end of the competition, half of the world's largest baguette was cut, spread by Nutella >- partner of the operation - and shared with the public. The other half of the baguette was given to charity >, becoming solidarity; was distributed the same evening during a food collection organized by the Celije Association of Suresnes for the homeless.&nbsp;
