AGI -&nbsp; There are 34 (of which 16 of German language >, as many as French and 2 of Italian language) the new recruits of the Corps of the Swiss Guard pontifical who have taken oath, today afternoon, in the Courtyard of San Damaso in the Vatican, on the occasion of the anniversary of the sack of Rome >.<br> As from tradition, this morning the new belongings to one of the world's most famous bodies were received by the Pontiff, to recall the episode of the sack of Rome (1527), in which 189 Guards lost their lives to defend Pope Clement VII against the army of Charles V.
<br> "To actively and intensively cultivate community life", perhaps even with trips to Rome or sports activities, going "against" with respect to the tendency of young people to "to spend free time alone with the computer or the mobile", Pope Francis asked them. That he also assured "The new barracks, > currently in the design phase, should make an important contribution to the reunification of the Guards and their families, which are currently forced to live a little dispersed due to lack of space".
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The rite of the oath >- in which it is proclaimed to protect and defend the Pope in office and all his legitimate successors, even at the risk of his life, as the ancestors have done in the past - happened on the banner of the Body of the Pontifical Swiss Guards and in the presence of the representative of the Pope, Monsignor Edgar Pena Parra, replaced for the General Affairs of the Secretariat of State.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<br At the solemn oath was a delegation of the Swiss Confederation, > led by President Viola Amherd with the President of the National Council, Eric Nussbaumer, and the President of the Council of States, Brigitte Eva Herzog. The head of the Army is represented by Brigadier Jacques Frederic Rudin, Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army. He also participated in the president of the Swiss Episcopal Conference, Monsignor Felix Gmur, bishop of Basel. This year's host canton delegation, Basel Campaign, is led by the president of the cantonal government, Monica Gschwind.
&nbsp;
Guided by Colonel Christoph Graf, the oldest army in the world > has the task of controlling access to the Vatican and the Apostolic Palace, to guarantee order and representation during papal ceremonies > and state receptions and to protect the College of Cardinals during the vacant seat. The Body includes guards from all the language regions of Switzerland.
<br The video of the ceremony sees the drums parade with the three guards leading the parade of young recruits, they have the helmet with the yellow and black feathers. The commander and the chaplain, Father Kolumban Reichlin OSB, review the entire bat. After their speeches, pronounced not only in Italian, but also with passages in French and German, the execution of the national anthems. The recruits, who wear the "Gran Gala", the gala uniform including about eight kilos of armor, which is worn only in three other circumstances in the year (for the papal blessing "Urbi et Orbi", at Christmas and Easter), parade in the courtyard, under the look of families and friends. They are called on by the sergeant and each proceeds with the solemn oath on the flag.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2> The oath formula
&nbsp; This is grasped with conviction with one hand while the other is raised with the three open fingers, symbol of trinity. The chaplain reads the formula? "I wish to serve faithfully, loyally and honorably the reigning Pontiff and his legitimate successors, to dedicate myself to them with all forces, sacrificing, if necessary, my life in their defense. I take the same duties towards the College of Cardinals during the holiday of the Apostolic See. I also promise the Commander and the other Superiors respect, fidelity and obedience. So I swear, God and our Patron Saints assist me."
<br The answer of each lipsticker is to observe "faithfully, loyally and honorably everything I have read at this moment. May God and our Patron Saints assist me."
