<span> Perched on a small bay, the village of Binibeca Vell on the Spanish island of Menorca has long been a magnet for tourists > who want to walk along its winding and narrow streets, flanked by whitewashed villas.&nbsp;</span>
<span>But while its popularity grows on social media, > triggering a selfie race taken along its pebble streets, residents threaten to block access to the village >.</span>
&nbsp;
“The problem is not the tourists,” said Óscar Monge, head of the group representing the 195 owners of Binibeca Vell>. On the other hand, he pointed his finger at officials who, in his opinion, abandoned the residents with the noise generated by the constant parade of visitors and with the garbage > which accumulates daily.
&nbsp;
What to face an excessive number of tourists is a debate that is affecting all of Spain, but also all the places that in recent years have been stormed by mass tourism.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
With the multiplication of Binibeca Vell's mentions on social media, the number of visitors rose to about 800,000 a year, most of which arrived between May and October, said Monge. This year residents expect a million visitors, he added.
&nbsp;
The threat of closing the complex is followed by years of complaints by residents. Last month, speaking with the news website ElDiario.es, a resident dismissed his frustration for the behavior of tourists visiting the village. “They entered the houses, sat on the chairs, took things, climbed on the walls, made outdoor parties to drink,” he said. “If it is not regulated, this will happen every summer”.&nbsp; Last year residents began to give a tour of lives, asking tourists to visit them only at certain times. This month the program was strengthened by asking tourists to stop only between 11.00 and 20.00.
